Richard L. Trumka, the President of the AFL-CIO, passed away today. He was a strong advocate for workers' rights and believed in the power of solidarity. Trumka's commitment to helping people stemmed from his personal experiences witnessing his father and grandfather's struggles during mine workers' strikes. He dedicated his life to fighting for fair pay, better working conditions, and the respect and representation of workers. Trumka believed that work has dignity and that justice and equality are crucial for a strong nation. The author of the article had the privilege of knowing Trumka and expresses their condolences to his family.